# Architectural Principles — corporate-data pipeline
# Role: AI agents write code. Humans do research & architecture.
# This file is the single source of truth for all coding decisions.

# ─── Code Style ───────────────────────────────────────────────
# PEP 8 strictly enforced (use ruff or flake8)
# Type hints on every function signature (mypy --strict)
# Google-style docstrings on every public function and class
# Max 50 lines per function — split if longer
# Max 120 characters per line
# English only: variable names, comments, docstrings, logs

# ─── Design ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SOLID: Single Responsibility — one class/module does one thing
# Dependency Injection: pass dependencies as arguments, no globals
# Open/Closed: extend existing modules, never duplicate logic
# No magic values: all thresholds, paths, model names in config
# Configuration over code: use env vars or config files
# Prefer composition over inheritance

# ─── No Duplication ───────────────────────────────────────────
# Common logic (classification, KPI parsing, schema validation)
#   lives in utils/ — import from there, never re-implement
# If you write the same logic twice — stop and refactor first

# ─── Data & I/O ───────────────────────────────────────────────
# Source files are READ-ONLY — never modify inputs
# All intermediate outputs go to outputs/ with ISO timestamp suffix
#   example: outputs/schema_2025-03-11T14-32-00.json
# Inter-stage format: JSON validated against JSON Schema
#   each stage validates its input before processing
# File paths come from config, never hardcoded in business logic

# ─── LLM-Specific ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# Prompts are separate files: prompts/*.jinja2 (not strings in code)
# Every LLM call logs: model, temperature, prompt_tokens,
#   completion_tokens, input_hash, output, timestamp
# Retry with exponential backoff: max 3 retries, base delay 2s
# Max context length is a config parameter (default: 8000 tokens)
# Temperature default: 0.0 for classification, 0.3 for generation
# Never parse LLM output with regex — use structured output (JSON mode)

# ─── Observability ────────────────────────────────────────────
# Structured logging in JSON format — no bare print() statements
# Use Python logging module with JSONFormatter
# Every pipeline stage logs on entry and exit:
#   - stage name, input parameters, output summary, duration_ms
# Separate audit.log for model decisions:
#   - what was resolved automatically (with confidence score)
#   - what was sent for human confirmation
#   - what was escalated as unresolvable
# Log levels: DEBUG for raw data, INFO for decisions, WARNING for
#   low-confidence results, ERROR for failures

# ─── Reproducibility ──────────────────────────────────────────
# requirements.txt uses pinned versions (== not >=)
# .env.example committed alongside .env (never commit .env)
# Random seeds set explicitly where randomness is used
# Each pipeline run writes a run_manifest.json:
#   - timestamp, input file hash (sha256), config snapshot,
#     model versions used, output file paths

# ─── Testability ──────────────────────────────────────────────
# Mock all external API calls — tests never hit the network
# Fixtures in tests/fixtures/ with real anonymized data samples
# Each pipeline stage must be runnable in isolation:
#   python -m pipeline.stage_01_extract --input data.json
# Unit tests cover: classifiers, parsers, schema validators
# Integration test: full pipeline on fixture file, assert schema

# ─── Pipeline Stages Contract ─────────────────────────────────
# Stage 01 — Structural Extractor (script):
#   input:  Excel file path
#   output: outputs/structural_<timestamp>.json
# Stage 02 — Semantic Analyzer (LLM):
#   input:  structural JSON
#   output: outputs/semantic_<timestamp>.json
#     contains: resolved[], confirm_queue[], escalate_queue[]
# Stage 03 — Human Review (CLI prompt or web form):
#   input:  confirm_queue + escalate_queue
#   output: outputs/human_review_<timestamp>.json
# Stage 04 — Schema Assembler:
#   input:  semantic JSON + human review JSON
#   output: outputs/final_schema_<timestamp>.json + .docx report
#
# Stage 05 — Query Agent (pipeline/stage_05*.py + app/query_ui.py)
#   05d — Executor (sandbox):
#     input:  Python code string
#     output: ExecutionResult(dataframe | None, error | None, code_used)
#     rules:  RestrictedPython sandbox, timeout=EXECUTOR_TIMEOUT,
#             whitelist imports only (EXECUTOR_ALLOWED_IMPORTS in config)
#             never writes files, never accesses network
#   05c — Generator (Text-to-Python):
#     input:  user query string + schema context (JSON subset of final_schema)
#     output: Python/pandas code string
#     rules:  prompts/query_generator.jinja2, JSON mode off (raw code),
#             temperature=QUERY_GEN_TEMPERATURE (default 0.0),
#             P1 implementation: pass full final_schema (no retrieval yet)
#   05e — Chart Builder:
#     input:  DataFrame + chart_type hint
#     output: PNG bytes | plotly Figure
#     rules:  auto-select chart type if hint=="auto"
#   05a — Embedder (P3, after 05c/05d work):
#     input:  final_schema JSON
#     output: ChromaDB collection in VECTOR_STORE_DIR
#   05b — Retriever (P3, after 05a):
#     input:  user query string
#     output: top-K schema fields (list of dicts)
#   app/query_ui.py — Streamlit UI:
#     operator sees: query box, result table, chart — NO code
#     admin panel: separate page /admin, password-protected
#     all config params editable in sidebar (session_state only)
#
# Stage 05 error model:
#   auto-retry up to QUERY_MAX_RETRIES — invisible to operator
#   after retries exhausted: show 'Не вдалося отримати відповідь'
#   write audit log entry with label failed_auto
#   admin receives notification (stdout warning + audit log)
#   operator NEVER sees generated code or error tracebacks

# ─── What Agents Must NOT Do ──────────────────────────────────
# Do not modify source Excel files
# Do not hardcode file paths — use config.py or env vars
# Do not swallow exceptions silently — log then re-raise
# Do not call LLM API more than once for the same input
#   (cache responses by input hash during development)
# Do not create parallel implementations of existing utilities

# ─── Paths ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# All paths in the project MUST be relative to the project root.
# Never use absolute paths in code, configs, or specs.
# Compute project root once in config.py using:
#   BASE_DIR = Path(__file__).parent
# Then derive all other paths from BASE_DIR:
#   OUTPUTS_DIR = BASE_DIR / "outputs"
#   SPECS_DIR   = BASE_DIR / "specs"
# Pass resolved Path objects between modules — never raw strings.
# Relative paths make the project portable across machines and CI.
# Exception: .env file values (OS-level) may contain absolute paths,
#   but config.py must wrap them with Path() and never expose them raw.
